<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-209-696  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 209 696.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Feb 26 1990 n579 p44(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>NIST: let's light a little fire! (Measuring Up!) (the NationalInstitute of Standards and Technology needs more governmentsupport) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Wittenberg, Roland.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>An analysis of the funding of the National Institute for Standardsand Technology (NIST) reveals that, despite a 22 percent increasein its FY 1991 budget, the 3,000-employee agency is underfunded.andO;This assertion is illustrated by making an assumption that theentire FY 1990 budget of $161.9 million goes to pay employees'salaries, benefits and overhead.andP;  Assuming 30 percentindustry-standard fringe benefits, the typical NIST base salary is$41,500, far under the approximately $50,000 base salary of theaverage industry electronics engineer in 1989.andP;  The TechnologyCompetitiveness Act of 1988, which renamed and restructured theNIST, itemized agency goals as enhancing the competitiveness of USindustry and continuing as the leading national laboratory formeasurement, calibration and quality assurance.andP;  Lobbyingrepresentatives for more NIST support is suggested.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Government FundingAnalysisGoals and ObjectivesGovernment AgencySalaryUnited States. National Institute of Standards and Technology.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>